"mode": "llm", "topic": "What is stereotype threat in STEM? Should we address it? And how?", "opinion": "Stereotype threat, a phenomenon wherein individuals at risk of conforming to negative stereotypes experience anxiety, undermining their performance. In STEM fields, this disproportionately affects women and underrepresented minorities (Yung et al., 1997), as seen in persistent gender gaps in engineering and physics. Addressing it is crucial for fostering equity. Interventions include promoting growth mindset (Yeukovich, Van Der Meere, & Thomae, 2010), emphasizing effort over innate ability, and creating inclusive curricula that reflect diverse contributions. Mentorship and role models also mitigate its effects by reshaping identity narratives. Institutions must proactively dismantle structural barriers while celebrating successes of underrepresented groups to counteract the self-fulfilling cycle stereotypes propagate. Ultimately, addressing stereotype threat aligns with broader goals of equitable education and societal progress, enabling all individuals to contribute fully without prejudice hindering potential.'"
